data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.3+ introduced **typed `TestDataRow<T>`** with `[TestMethod(typeof(...))]`, eliminating the `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestDataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[TestDataRow("invalid", false)]
[TestDataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

For **dynamic data** (computed at runtime), you can return typed tuples:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**
- **`TestDataRow`** — replaces inline `[DataRow(...)]` with compile-time type checking on each argument.
- **Typed `DynamicData`** — the property returns `IEnumerable<T>` (tuples or custom types) instead of `IEnumerable<object[]>`, so mismatched types are caught at compile time.

Both require **MSTest 3.3+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` / `MSTest.Sdk`).
